< review>
My buddy and I were looking to get some desserts and we found this place. We had stopped by this place before but they were closed. Today, they were open and it was a pleasant surprise. They had pies, macaroons, cookies, cakes and they also sell food which I was not interested in. The lady that tended us was so helpful, friendly and took the time to answer all of our questions. We decided to get some tiramisu, cheesecake, cannoli and I don‚Äôt remember the name of the last piece but it had custard in it. All were so yummy except for their cannoli which I didn‚Äôt care for. The experience was really nice and we enjoyed ourselves. We will definitely be coming back for more.

<response>None< /response><GmapID>0x80e852aa2fae8b05:0xfe21b9b6a4669630< /GmapID><review>Anytime I am in Oxnard or Ventura I will try to eat here. LOVE their house salad with chicken...I get it every single time. Even if I decide to try something else there, I will always ALSO get one of those because they are just too good. I like to get the dressing on the side because it is pretty large and if you want to save some for the next day the dressing of course makes the lettuce soggy and gross when sitting for a long time. There is not a lot of seating there and they are usually pretty busy, so most of the time I will just get my food to go. Keep in mind it says online that they close at I believe 6 or something but that is only for the bakery. If you want lunch they stop serving around 2 or 2:30 I think so I recommend calling just to make sure. They also have great quiches and if you like sweets they have lots and lots of options. The cow cookies are adorable and delicious which we used to get all the time but now that our diets have changed they are no longer an option for us. <date>1425662874341< /date><Rating>3</Rating>< Text>
This is only a review on the baked goods from Royal Bakery & Caf√©, so keep that in mind. Their sandwiches and salads actually looked pretty darn tasty, so I might have to go back and try some of those.

As far as the baked goods, we tried the chocolate chip cookies (without nuts), the blackout cookie, a pear and berry coffeecake and a fruit tart. Overall, I can‚Äôt really complain, but I can‚Äôt really dream about them either. They‚Äôre decent, but not amazing.

The cookies? Um. Well, they‚Äôre adequate. You can probably get some that are very similar from a grocery store.

The coffeecake was kind dry. This let me down the most. I get that coffeecake should be dry, as it goes with coffee, but it was dry to the tune of over-baked, not necessarily intentional.

As you might expect being in a growing area, the fruit tart had some decent fruit. Plus, the shell wasn‚Äôt too shabby, though the custard was a touch eggy.

Overall, adequate, but not spectacular.< /Text>

<gmapID>0x80952f78933fb97f:0xa79c82238fe3f2f7< /gmapID><Rate>4< /Rate>< Review>
I had the combo bowl with 2 meats, rice, and veg. I underestimated the portion size, when I opened it I scoffed at it but 3/4 in I'm like, huh, it's actually enough and I'm a big guy. I got the original beef which is delicious! I will say, it's a little on the greasy side but it just has this taste i crave after a while. The yakiniku/BBQ beef is the same except saucy and sweet. I had the spring rolls, they're great but overpriced. Overall, I wanted more Japanese items like ramen, gyoza, takoyaki, and mochi sweets but I'll take what I can get. The original beef is in my opinion they're only saving grace.< /Review>

< review>
I eat there at least once a week. Manager is very friendly despite what others would have you believe and he even lowers the price on my orders for being such a frequent customer. Also they have only ever gotten my order wrong once in like 3 years or so of eating there pretty much every week often times more than once (it was a new employee taking my order over the phone and they were very busy at the time so pretty much what you'd expect anyways). Really don't get all the crap this place is getting from some people. Believe it or not they get really busy sometimes and have trouble doing everything at the same level of quality they normally have with their small staff of like 3-6 people (but that doesn't happen often enough to warrant hiring more people however).<//review>

<text>My husband and I had dinner at Solare for a little date night. We ventured out of East Village because we've heard great things about this place.

The food was delicious. We had the Classic Pappardelle Bolognese and Risotto Tartufo e Capesante and both were tasty. 5 out of 5.

<Review>Might not be fair to rate this place right now considering the must for outside seating. We stayed because there was no wait for a party of 4 at 6:30 on on a Saturday. They were upfront and told us the only seating available was on the grass with no heat lamps. This of course is because of the rules surrounding social distancing and the restaurant is doing their best to add outside seating. No surprise, we got a bit cold. Not the restaurant's fault. The location is right under the airport takeoff flight path. We had to halt conversation or yell with some of the takeoffs. Kind of cool at first, but not after awhile. Again, not the restaurant's fault. Service was a bit slow. This may have been due to the increased distance servers needed to travel from kitchen or bar to table. Busing of the table was a bit incomplete. For some reason when he removed things from our table he neglected to take the empty beer can (x 2) and water bottle cap. The food was good but not exceptional. Years ago we ate here and I recall really enjoying it. I would eat here again even with the 3 stars I gave this visit for the overall experience. It was still good to be outside and enjoying a meal with friends during this crazy COVID-19 time.</Review>< Rate>

<Text>Great ambiance and delicious food!!< /Text><pics>None<//pics><response>None<//response><gmap_id>0x80deab0424098d6b:0xad7ea551b3f5c87</gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<user_id>105626123068977288302<//user_id><user_name>Terry Kane<//user_name>< time>
1612150495563< /time>
<Rating>1</Rating>< review>
We drove over 20 miles each way to dine at Solare for a special-occasion dinner, based on previous experiences there with great food, including one during COVID restrictions in Oct. 2020.  This time we were very disappointed and came away annoyed.
First problem was that the waiter explained we couldn't get an Arnold Palmer, because they can't serve anything from a pitcher due to COVID restrictions. (Okay fine, but why not have bottled ice tea and lemonade in the kitchen in the interim?).  Bottled water was the option for the non-wine-drinkers, so we ordered a bottle, which was one glass each, and were never offered another until we had to ask for one late in the meal.  (Despite the empty bottle sitting on the end of the table through the meal.)
No bread was offered to the table at all.  Most respectable Italian restaurants provide it, or at least offer it.
We ordered the only two appetizers on the menu. One was Bruschetta ($16) which came with 3 tasty spreads but only 7 very small bits of toast about 1 1/2 inches square, You'd think that for a party of 4, you could afford to  put out 8 or 12 bits of toast so everyone could have a few pieces (they were too small to break in half...).  7 pieces?   The other was the charcuterie (another $16 - unless you want cheese with it, which adds $6 for what I'd assume is a few small slices of cheese, judging from the small portions of the three meat selections).
I ordered the lamb shank ($36), described as "Incredible" on the menu. It was very small.  I‚Äôve had chicken legs with more meat than this shank.
The others‚Äô entrees were quite small as well, and all took a very long time to be served. No one mentioned that their entree was anything special, and this group would normally say so.
The waiter never checked with us to ask ‚ÄúIs everything okay?‚Äù or ‚ÄúHow was everything?‚Äù
Maybe he already knew.
Not sure what‚Äôs happened to this place.<//review>

<userid>113298601154133645590< /userid>< user_name>
Colin Shaw</user_name>
< Date>
1554054233649< /Date>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
We couldn't have asked for a better dining experience than the one we had last night. Tommy was a real expert with the wine and beer menu and guided me to the perfect beer. All of the staff was attentive to all of our needs and made sure that everything from the drinks to appetizers, entrees and dessert came out to our liking.

The focaccia is out of this world. I'd go back just for this alone. However, we had other awesome sides such as buratta and fried calamari. Each appetizer was genuinely good.

The main courses we had were cooked to perfection. Definitely one of the best risottos I have ever eaten. My wife had a pasta de mare that she thought was outstanding.

The restaurant is worthy of being a go-to spot when you are in the mood for Italian food. Great food, great service and a really reasonable price considering much of the ingredients are fresh and locally sourced.<//text>

<date>1579489596150<//date><Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
We came for the San Diego Restaurant Week dinner menu. I had the octopus appetizer, and it was spectacular: poached in olive oil and then briefly fried, it was tender and flavorful, and accompanied with a tomato/olive/caper sauce. My spouse enjoyed the lobster bisque and then the fettuccine with shrimp. I had the fish of the day, which was ono. We tried both of the desserts: a panna cotta with a bittersweet chocolate sauce on the side (excellent) and a special cocktail. Neither of us cared for the gin-based concoction, but then, neither of us have a taste for gin.< /Text>

< text>
The food here goes above and beyond what ever words are used to describe it. We have enjoyed everything on the menu and appreciate the lengths chef Arcusio et al, has gone to, to source, honor, and prepare each ingredient. One of our favorites is the risotto with scallops. It is not to be missed, the scallops are seared to perfection and the risotto is creamy and flavorful while not being "heavy". The cocktails are a phenomenon on their own, and are worth exploring in depth.  The service is immaculate and deserves to receive equal adulation. All the awards they have received are proof that we are not alone in our opinions and I am grateful they have received such  accolades. Most importantly though, is the way the staff treats you like your family which proves you can enjoy world class cuisine in SD without any of the pretentiousness.<//text>

<user_name>John Caldwell<//user_name><text>We were with a large party who reserved the outside patio.  I don't recommend reserving the patio if you are doing anything but drinking, because there just isn't enough room.

It was buffet style with a single pasta (penne with meat sauce), two salads (a Caesar and a baby greens salad with strawberries and blue cheese), with tea, soda, and water included.  The food was good, but not for the $30 per person price tag plus 20% gratuity on top of that and whatever it cost to reserve the space.  I was surprised there was no bread.

The service was terrible.  You had to get your own water at a station on the patio; and yes, the glasses are small.  If you wanted tea or soda, you had to go to the bar and get it yourself.  The only service provided was bussing the dirty plates off of the tables, and they were very slow at that.  Ten percent is the traditional buffet tip, so I have no idea how they felt the service we received was worth 20%.

I can't speak to normal dining, but absolutely do not recommend going here with a large party.<//text>< Date>
1555015359269<//Date>

< Review>
I have been here several times, and it's becoming one of my favorites in Point Loma.  The atmosphere is kind of dark and moody in a very good way.  The wine list is very nice across middle to higher price points.  I like to visit when I  have time to enjoy an appetizer and start a nice bottle before dinner.  I'm pleased with the pasta and meatballs dishes especially, and the pizza is good too.  It can be very busy on a weekend, but usually easy to get a table on a week night... They have a wine special one night, so check the web site for that.  It can get a little noisy if the place is full.  Enjoy!<//Review>

<UserId.>108242073328637707712< /UserId.><user_name>samantha baker<//user_name>< Date>

< Rating>
2< /Rating>
<Text>It saddens me, as a member of the culinary world to write this review. My boyfriend and i decided to try this place out for our special NYE dinner.  I guess , quite possibly, based on the reviews and the price of the dinner ($85/plate) we had decent expectation.

Conceptually, i think the food had the right idea. As well the right plating...everything was beautiful. The moment we started to devour these beautiful plates.. my taste buds started screaming. They were begging for more flavor, more salt, more sugar, literally more anything.

I claimed the pork tenderloin as my choice for the evening, and its texture was like it had been boiled. I could barely cut into it. The taste was bland, and the apples served with it were coated in a pan sauce i believe?  The sauce seemed like it needed to be reduced. The sauce was watery and tasted just like stock was poured over my plate. The apples that littered my plate had no texture, no flavor, and could have easily been misconstrued for potatoes.

My Boyfriend got enough gnocchi for two people, but again, it was beautiful they were prepared properly but lack luster in taste. The only thing we both liked this entire evening was the soup.

After working in this business, i understand the point of set menu on nights like NYE. I understand the limitations are to keep the night flowing smoothly and expedited on time.

I guess even tho the dessert wasn't bad, i expected more than ice cream.
Again the serving size was for two people.  I, an avid chocolate lover, felt like it was too much.

The one star is very deserving of the waitress. She was the only thing that kept me calm. She could tell i was displeased and she very graciously  added a discount to our bill.

Which brings me to the last point. On the bottom of the receipt, it has a (usually) handy tip calculator, i just wanted to add that it may need to be looked over. It was a tad incorrect ( by about $6).

But, i do feel like the team should be able to understand that at the end of the day , people are choosing to spend an important evening at your restaurant, make it worth their time. Otherwise, why else are you doing it?
I guess i'll end this with we were just Very disappointed and felt that we had been "duped" .<//Text><pics>None</pics><Response>None</Response>< gmapID>
0x80deab0424098d6b:0xad7ea551b3f5c87</gmapID>

< rate>
5<//rate>
<review>Located in Liberty Station, the team at Solare have done a great job making the place elegant and welcoming. The place seems to be divided into two sections, with more formal dining to the left and the bar and additional seating on the right. Both offer the same great menu and ambiance. On certain nights, Solare has live entertainment which adds even more reasons to love this hidden gem in Point Loma.  If it's available, ask for the table in the wine cellar, it's a glass room in the middle of the restaurant that stocks an amazing selection of wine bottles to enjoy. You can also ask to be seated at the kitchen table where the chef can prepare selections for you to enjoy. A large private room for special events is available, and they have outside dining as well if that's more your thing. We're definitely coming back to Solare, as the food was by far some of the best we've had in Point Loma. (Happy Hour, by the way, is pretty great, too!)<//review><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Response>

< text>
Excellent Italian food< /text>
<date>1568118134882< /date><response>None</response><Gmap_id>0x80deab0424098d6b:0xad7ea551b3f5c87<//Gmap_id><username>Brenda Davis< /username><UserId.>104511781124174940514<//UserId.>< rate>

< pics>

</record></dataset><record>
<user>108685370139018629938<//user>< Name>
Jay Keyes</Name>
< Time>
1497383466661<//Time>
< rating>
5< /rating>
<Text>Located in Liberty Station, Solare Ristorante is an authentic Italian restaurant with a Sicily-born chef who executes southern Italian cuisine. In other words, if you're looking for "chicken parm" and "pasta primavera," look elsewhere!

I am picky about Italian, which is to also say that San Diego's mostly lame Italian options have been a source of frustration and angst since moving here last year. Solare is one of a handful of Italian restaurants in San Diego that could survive in New York City.

I recommend the "Tartara di Tonno," Solare's Sicilian interpretation of tuna tartare: a meaty cake of chopped raw ahi tuna with capers, horseradish, basil, and garlic. The vibrant pink color of this appetizer makes it as nice to look at as it is to eat.

Do you like meatballs? Try the "Polpette al Forno." The smooth texture and delicate flavor of these small Subway-sized veal meatballs are not lost in a thick marinara sauce, as they instead swim in a collagen-rich stock-y sauce that is lightly touched with tomato. The meatballs are topped with crispy arugula leaves and grated parmigiano reggiano.

The "Pappardelle Verdi Salsiccia e Carciofi" is a spicy pasta dish constructed with spinach pappardelle noodles, sweet fennel sausage, chopped artichokes, tomatoes, chilies, and covered in large, thin slices of pecorino crotonese cheese. Solare indicates that all pasta served during the course of a day is made from scratch that morning, and this is evident by the quality and freshness of their hefty and terrific pappardelle. The citrusy crotonese is the ideal cheese for this heavy (and oily) bowl of meat and noodles.

If you're looking for a heavier meal, you'll want to order the "Ossobuco di Maiale," which is very similar to a traditional ossobuco alla milanese, but with a 22oz Salmon Creek pork shank instead of the traditional veal shank. Braised meat rarely ever will be done better than it is here -- the meat was velvety, soft, rich, and had incredible flavor. The marinated cremini mushrooms were also insanely excellent, my only complaint being that there were just three of them on my plate. The shank itself rested on a bed of creamy risotto flavored with a tangy gremolata and a perfect amount of saffron.

The interior of the restaurant is stylish, with teak wood furnishings, stone accents, and a glass-enclosed cube-like wine room that separates the bar area from the dining room. There is also a ton of outdoor seating.

Solare is a fantastic destination in San Diego for Italian, as they have hit all the right notes on taste, presentation, creativity, price, decor, and service.< /Text><pictures>None</pictures>< Response>
{'time': 1497767537687, 'text': 'My name is Randy, and I am the owner of Solare.   Thank you so much for the kind words and the detailed and positive review.\n\nI do really appreciate the detail - please let me know the next time you may dine with us again - I would like to say "hi" and explain more about what we do.  My email is randy@solarelounge.com\n\nMy team and I will do everything we can to have future dining experiences at Solare be just as good.   Look forward to seeing you again soon!'}</Response>

100900010911970750562</user_id>
< rating>
5<//rating>
<pics>None<//pics><Name>Jonathan Adler<//Name>< text>
Solare excels in all respects as one of the best Italian fine dining establishments.

The restaurant is large and very well designed, featuring gorgeous private dining rooms with wine rack walls as well as a full bar and spacious dining areas.

The Staff recommended the Tasting Menu which consisted of:

Insalata-lettuce wedge in egg mouse with mustard seed caviar. This was a superb and memorable combination of flavors.

Ravioli in brown butter, sage, arugula with ricotta

Papardelle al Sugo di Salsiccia-house made pasta aged a year with sausages and pistachos. This dish is a winner featuring a delicious crunchiness and deep flavor.

The highlight was my first ever Hawaiian Monchong fish in smoked tomato broth and fingerling potatoes. The fish was perfectly cooked, very fresh and tender.

My wine selection, Montepulciano was exceptional and perfectly complemented the food.

I also had a Voltaire mixed drink which I highly recommend.

Before and afterwards, the Owner and head chef from Sicily were gracious enough to welcome me as a guest.

Solare also features a gorgeous outdoor patio and is full of art which really enhances the mood.

Verdict: Solare is well deserving of its #1 rating in San Diego magazine for Italian restaurants and is easily within the 100 best in the nation in my experience.

Kudos to the exceptional team there.</text>

<rate>1</rate><Review>wow was this place is a HUGE disappointment.  First we get there and it looks decent.  we go to the hostess stand and the guy says "do you have reservations?"  me, "No".  him, "well, we'll fit you in but you should make reservations in the future because we really busy on Saturday night." um.......i looked around and saw about 10 tables open plus all the seat on the patio, which is where we wanted to see anyways.  Strike one.....lie and make it seem like you are super busy especially when i look around and i see half the restaurant empty.  AND.....while, i'm sitting outside and i can see how many more people go in and it definitely wasn't enough to fill all your open tables. AND definitely don't lie to me and say that the tables in the front near the heat lamp is reserved when the couple after me asks if they can sit there and you let them.WTF?!

My next problem was the service.  we waiting 10 minutes to get water and our drinks ordered.  the food itself..........i've had better at olive garden.  We had the prosciutto and salami board to start..... um, 4 pieces of prosciutto and about 10 pieces of salami.......seriously?!  that was the biggest waste of $15 ever.  My wife had the Osso Bucco, which is pork by the way if you don't read carefully, it's not the traditional veal shank which was kinda tough and had no flavor at all on top of "risotto"....like about 2 tablespoons of risotto.  I had the linguine alla pecatora......meh......tasted like they opened up a can of Del Monte Stewed Tomatoes and just mixed.

< Review>
This is the best cafe in the neighborhood. It's our go to place when we don't feel like cooking. I was sad when Actual Cafe closed down but Paradise Cafe is an upgrade. The staff is always super friendly and helpful and the food is delicious. Our server Hannah went out of her way to make sure all of our needs were met. They also have a play corner for kids which means my husband and I actually get to eat our food without interruption! If you're in the neighborhood stop by Paradise cafe.</Review>

<user>101490505371261450741< /user><user_name>Donna Elazar</user_name><date>1553572954320</date><rating>4< /rating><Text>I was visiting from out of town and I liked the menu here so we decided to give it a try. I had the fig, prosciutto, truffle, and arugula pizza. It had great flavors and textures! Salty and sweet, soft and crunchy. The crust/dough could have used some salt though.

My biggest complaint was the little bits of corn meal all over the bottom of the pizza was burnt. I did not like that taste, and I also believe burnt foods may not be good for health, either. Also, I'd like to see more warm vegetarian menu options here.

My partner said the meat in his turkey sandwich was very high quality and tasty. The portions were great, we ate everything again for dinner the next day, making the seemingly high initial price tag very worth it and a good value for the quality. I appreciate the mindfulness around organic produce/responsibly farmed meat.

I enjoyed the ambiance in the place, the music, and the counter service. There were only 3 other people there for dinner Sunday night before close, so I'm glad it wasn't crowded like some of the other reviews mention. <Rate>5< /Rate><text>Wow, this place is amazing for breakfast. Lots of varied options for every taste. I had the Paradise Egg Sandwich, and it might have been the best egg sandwich I've had in... I don't know how long because I don't recall having a better one.

Someone else reviewed their tots, which I think was in reference to one of their menu items that included tots - because their regular tots as an add-on to other meals are great, but basically exactly what you'd hope tater tots would be - crispy fried potatoes in tot form. Delicious, but not something I'd seek out when they have SO MANY amazing options to choose from. I can't say I was disappointed though.

Also got a cafe mocha, which is not really my norm; usually they're too sweet, but on the recommendation from the staff I tried it, and she was absolutely right - not too sweet, more of a dark chocolate, just right by me.

Everyone working at the place was really friendly and chatty but not invasive. I definitely have a new favorite breakfast spot in Oakland!< /text>< Pictures>

<Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
I think this is a hidden gem for brunch among all the overrated brunch places in the Berkeley area. Food quality is high (have had eggs, french toast) at a great price. Fresh squeezed orange juice actually tastes like it is 100% fresh squeezed and not cut with concentrated OJ like other places.
Their home made jam is a nice touch and some times I will order a side of toast just to have the jam.  :)

Workers seemed to take pride in the food quality. It can be a little busy/cramped at times, but not as ridiculous as some other places that serve mediocre brunch.<//Text>

< username>
geraldcayt</username>
<text>Was surprised to find Paradise Park Cafe open today as I walked around the neighborhood. The cafe took over the Actual Cafe location around January 2017. Took a while to open. Today was their official grand opening.

I had an almond milk mocha with an almond croissant, $9.19 total including a $1 tip. I guess that is what a coffee drink and pastry costs now. They do NOT have a senior citizen discount and no opening specials. The drink and pastry were okay, the mocha was as I asked for, not sweet, but lacked a strong chocolate flavor. The almond croissant had little flavor.

Even though they had around 10 people on their staff, the opening day showed that there was a lot of management and training to do. Some things I noticed:

- No dish pan available, unclear where dirty dishes go

- The instructions from the counter person about how to get on the wifi were incorrect, there was no hub called ParadiseParkCafe. The password I was given did not work for the two hubs, Paradise1 and Paradise2.

_____ Some good stuff

+ toilets clean and functional.

+ staff friendly and courteous.

+ lots of seating with indoor and outdoor options,  individual tales that could be pushed together for a group.

+ large number of food choices and drinks on menu -- mostly "healthy"

- There was no bulletin board for a cafe that advertises as a community organization. Also, most of the patrons were visually and hearing plugged into their electronics -- again not much community.

- Unclear where to wait for coffee drink or food ordered.<//text>< date>

<resp>None< /resp><Text>We were introduced to this place by a colleague from work. He raved about their food and so I brought my office staff for a treat. We all loved the food! But when we had the chance to discuss our experience in terms of service, we all agreed that the Mother, Pina (the main cook) and her daughter, the server did not treat us well. They were friendly to other customers who were white but noticeably different with us. Because of their good food, our first not pleasant experience did not stop us from coming back. On our next visit my children who are Italian food lovers joined me and my office crew. It was again pretty obvious that while the daughter and server was very chatty with other white customers, she was hardly talking to us and forgetting our orders and needed to be followed up. We did try to be friendly guests but for some reason, we as a group, were not appealing to them. When kitchen is not so busy, Pina would get out and talk to customers but not to us. Not taking offense to our experiences, we patronized them 2 more times by ordering party trays but even these were not a good experience. We stopped patronizing Pina's since then. There are other well deserving restaurants out there.I don't want to name our bad experiences but you can read between the lines and determine for yourself.</Text><gmap_id>0x80dcdbd88531d517:0xa1180c86eb09d085< /gmap_id><date>1584529393901<//date><rate>1< /rate><Name>Cheri Platte< /Name></record>

<Review>I love Pina's Bistro Restaurant from the very first time I saw it (it was closed) when I stopped next door for other business. 2 months ago, I actually visited it for the very first time! I had The best creamy and delicious pasta and I met Pina!!! This evening, I found out that her recipe for the Alfredo doesn't include the strong chemicals other Alfredo sauces have since she prepares it in a natural and in the most natural way. <userid>108287380108185503152< /userid><review>If I could give Pina's 10 stars I would!  We drove 3 hours to go to Pina's because the name caught my attention , we share the same name and I was intrigued.  After reading the reviews I knew I had to try it. This is an authentic Italian family run Restaurant.   Pina makes everything from scratch just like I would at home. The whole meal was scrumptious, from the fresh home made bread I was hooked. We had calamari,  salad, lasagna and her special home made sausage alla pizzaiola.  Finished with the best homemade tiramisu,  cannoli and espresso. Needless to say this was the best dining experience.  Pina and her daughter Rachel were so attentive , friendly and a pleasure to interact with and made us feel like part of the family. Definitely worth the drive. She even sent me home with some of her homemade bread. This store has top-notch customer support.

Bri helped me pick out new shoes for running long distance. From the moment I walked in until I left with my new shoes, the service was outstanding. She definitely made my experience at the store worthy of stopping. We spent almost an hour picking the right shoes for me.

The prices of the shoes will vary depending on the needs of the person. I need shoes with more cushioning, so I had to spend a little more than what I am used to. Regardless of the prices, I appreciated that Bri kept in mind my budget and offered to show me shoes on the lower price side.

If I have to recommend a store for someone looking for running advice, this will be my go to.< /Review>

First off, let me say that I am NOT a runner.  However, my sister and my grown nephews are all avid runners.  I have purchased shoes at A Snail's Pace for my own daughters when they did cross country in school, and those experiences were great.  But the reason I am posting this review now is that, being pressed for time to get my Christmas shopping done, and being a full-time worker and a full-time student at the same time, going to malls and stores for holiday shopping is just not a possibility for me right now.

Today I called the store, and spoke with Melissa, the manager on duty.  She was able to look up the history of one of my nephews and help me pick out a present for him based upon my nephew's past purchases, including sizes and brand names.  She was so gracious in her customer service, I wish she had a manager whom I could call and give the compliment.  She helped me choose an item, took my credit card information over the phone, and is shipping the item to my house directly (shipping is no charge, by the way).  I fully recommend A Snail's Pace for all your running needs.< /review>

< Review>
First off, this is a sex club.
Don't expect to go here and get a drink and dance.  It's not that kind of place.
Second, this club is what you are willing to make of it.
If you bring a partner and go have fun, you will really enjoy the play-space.
There is everything from open room beds, stipper polls, semi-private rooms, video rooms, even a small dungeon!
Think of it as a strip club/sex club but without the provided strippers.

It's an adult's playground.

The best nights to come are Fridays and the 3rd Saturday of every month.
Every Friday is couples night, and there is always a LOT of action going on and around the club.
The 3rd Saturday is "Ball night" and it's always packed and a lot of fun.

If you are a single guy and coming to have fun or hoping to get lucky, I HIGHLY recommend coming on a Friday night.  A good portion of the couples that come to play are looking for a fun guy to add to their sexual fun.
Come well dressed, be polite and you'll have a great time.</Review>

< review>
Authentic food from northern Vietnam.  I had bun dau mam tom (which include a special shrimp paste sauce,  a salty, fragrant sauce with deep fried tofu, boiled pork belly, deep fried meat cake, noodle and fresh vietnamese herbs.) Be careful with the sauce,  it needs a bit of lemon or lime to balance it out.
Wet also ordered bun Cha Ha noi. Similar components,  except the meat is prepared with coconut juice and fish sauce.<//review>

This in an interesting restaurant. The smell upon entering is not something you can call pleasant.  It smelled like old fish sauce and a bit of old rag mixed with heavy fish broth. The food came out and it was pretty good, good enough to eat but not good enough to make me want to come back anytime soon. Most of the food came out within 5 minutes of ordering.  It makes you wonder how they get it ready so fast?! We ordered some escargot.  It was heavily garlic-spiced flavored.    If the garlic was cooked out a bit, it would have been better.<//review>

< Review>
I love this place! Portion is very big you can probably share between 2 people if you don't eat a lot. They don't have a lot of selections but every single item on the menu is spot on! Prices are also on the low side - less than $10 per item.

Parking can be a little tricky if you come for dinner since they don't have a lot of parking and you will probably have to park in the residential area right next to it. They also have a rewards program if you come a lot and pay by cash!</Review>

<pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPCn_150_6Ox_KERUbQ5O5fNWuZiI0zWosrS2jw=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNUgLKaRE8zMwFz-isWDIDfHdx6gLwm6ESpq0de=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOIUzVnlUxaZkOkzF9U8kBZfcfFq-gjGOMz2HTQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNYtsu9QtHvG5LLZqmT55vI73OAX-nNnl37N2H8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures></record>

<date>1534909433938</date>< pics>
None<//pics>
< text>
One of my favorite places to eat bun cha Ha Noi. They make it with your choice or regular vermicelli noodles or flat rice sheets. I had tried both and although both are good but the flat rice sheets are my favorite.

Their service is fast and everyone is so nice. They speak both English and Vietnamese. Servers are patient and will make suggestions if you are unsure what you want.

I came here for Mother's day and received a free Macaron Ice Cream sandwich. They were delicious! I would definitely recommend this place! A must try if you are in town.< /text>

<Review>The Bun Cha Ha Noi is satisfying and delicious! It's on the salty side, so definitely have a drink with it. That won't be too hard because they have a large selection of flavored and milk teas to choose from. The honey boba is soft and chewy. It's on the sweet side though, but I liked it. I've been here twice in the past week, and the service is was quick and friendly both times. Depending when you go, parking can be tricky and you may have to park further down the street by the houses if the parking lot is full. The entree selection is smaller compared to other restaurants, but that just means your choices are probably all good.</Review><pictures>None</pictures><resp>None< /resp><gmapID>0x80dd28901cdc306f:0xa39be0546952ebf4<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>

<rate>2</rate><UserId.>105042781435068184937< /UserId.>< user_name>
Linh Do< /user_name>
< Date>
1529541587430</Date>
< pictures>
None</pictures>
< Resp>
None</Resp>
< Review>
You know they give out free milk tea if you write a review right? That means you can't really trust the review system anymore! Well, I got fooled by all the advertisement. Advice to people who want to try good Vietnamese food: this is not the place!!!

Rear parking is limited, side parking is scary and weird.
Inside decor is nice.

Service is bad! They forgot about half of our order, then the waitress came out and ask us "oh the food is not out yet?" Uhmmm I don't work here girl, idk?!!!

Food:
Bun cha Hanoi is supposed to be the signature dish of any Hanoi restaurant here in OC, but they made it poorly: the meat cake was dry, the fish sauce was really salty... If you know Vietnamese cuisine you know that the sauce is the most important part of many many dishes. They failed with this signature one.
Bun dau mam tom was a 3.5/5, I have to give it to them on the mam tom though, they made a good job with the sauce on this dish. Just the cha com was terrible, it's like eating a very moist sticky rice cake being fried...
Bun ca was a disappointment! The soup isn't sour enough. It seems to me like they don't put in the effort of making the different broth for different noodle soup. Bun ca has its own kind of broth, pho has its own kind of broth, bun rieu has its own kind of broth....

In conclusion, I don't like it!!! You might get better dishes than we did maybe.... At your own risk you come in!< /Review>
</record>

<UserId.>115272165125261998433<//UserId.>< user_name>
Kimmie Nguyen</user_name>
<Date>1526069562779</Date><Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
I really enjoy dining here at any time of the day.
It is absolutely delicious and the presentation of the food is well represented.

I was craving Bun Cha Ha Noi and found this restaraunt on yelp. I wanted to try a new restaraunt and drove here. The restaraunt is "not in your face" and from the direction I was heading, I had to make a U turn. I did not have trouble finding parking, but this place could get packed.

We were quicklyy seated and the staff were very nice and polite. We sat at the booth and it was spacious. They hire just the right amount of staff that you do not need to chase them down if you needed something. The menu was straightforward and there were photos to go along with the food items. I ordered Bun Cha Ha Noi and my mom ordered a variety platter. The food came out very quickly. The food presentation was adorable with the banana leaf and so. They put a whole bottle of water on your table for your and their convenience. The cups are cute and perfect size.

Bun Cha Ha Noi had the right amount of additives to it, it was very flavorful with vermicelli noodles and the meat were fantastic. They make it just right and perfected the dish that their was no pork smell to it. I really enjoyed it and so did my mom. I have not tried their desserts but can guarantee that their main dishes are worth the drive, at least for me since I am not around the area. I also signed up for their phone list to earn credits to receive freebies, it is a neat concept that I do not see most Vietnamese restaraunt does.

We had such a great meal, my mom asked me to drive her back here again the next time. And again, we had a good time, it was not packed when we arrived in the morning. The service, again, was excellent and the food was yummy. I highly reccommend this restaraunt.< /Review>
